South Korea recorded a new daily high of 38,691 COVID-19 cases on Sunday, Yonhap news agency has reported, with health authorities confirming that the country has now surpassed one million cases nationwide. South Korea saw its first confirmed COVID-19 case on January 20, 2020. An aggressive strategy of tracking, tracing, masking and quarantining helped it to blunt that initial wave and keep overall cases and deaths low without widespread lockdowns, but the spread of the Omicron variant is driving case numbers to new highs. Deaths have remained low in the country, however, with 15 new deaths reported as of midnight Saturday, according to the Korea Disease Control and Prevention Agency. Minors Still Detained In Syria Prison Attacked by IS, Says UN Wife Reportedly Stabs Husband’s Nephew Over Broken Mirror Daily cases are nearly five times higher than two weeks ago, when the Omicron variant began to dominate, but serious infections have remained at manageable levels so far, authorities have said. In an effort to curb the virus, officials on Friday announced they would extend the current toughened social distancing measures for at least another two weeks, including a 9 p.m. curfew on businesses and a six-person limit for private gatherings. South Korea has reported 1,009,688 COVID-19 cases, with 6,873 deaths. Some 86 percent of the country’s 52 million population is fully vaccinated, with over 54.5 percent having received booster shots.